Subject: [PATCH] newlib: 16-byte malloc alignment for VMX/AltiVec quadwords

The Cell PPU has __BIGGEST_ALIGNMENT__ == 16 (VMX vec_float4), but the
dlmalloc default alignment is 2*SIZE_SZ == 8 under ILP32.  Code that stores
a vec_float4 into heap memory via stvx/lvx (e.g. vectormath Vector3 from
operator new[] under -std=gnu++98, which has no over-aligned new) writes to
(addr & ~0xf), one 16-byte slot below an 8-aligned block, clobbering the
adjacent malloc chunk header and corrupting the heap (manifests as a crash
in a later free()).  Honor __BIGGEST_ALIGNMENT__ when it exceeds the
historical default so plain malloc satisfies vector types in every language
mode.  Matches the reference libc's 16-byte allocations.

diff --git a/newlib/libc/stdlib/_mallocr.c b/newlib/libc/stdlib/_mallocr.c
index 56968cbd1..1abab88ca 100644
--- a/newlib/libc/stdlib/_mallocr.c
+++ b/newlib/libc/stdlib/_mallocr.c
@@ -1402,8 +1402,22 @@ nextchunk-> +-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+
 
 #define SIZE_SZ                (sizeof(INTERNAL_SIZE_T))
 #ifndef MALLOC_ALIGNMENT
-#define MALLOC_ALIGN           8
+/* The allocator must return memory aligned for the largest type the
+   target supports.  On the Cell PPU, VMX/AltiVec quadwords require
+   16-byte alignment (__BIGGEST_ALIGNMENT__ == 16); the historical
+   2*SIZE_SZ default (8 under ILP32) under-aligns them.  A vec_float4
+   stored into such memory via stvx/lvx — which mask the low 4 bits of
+   the effective address — then silently writes 16 bytes to the next
+   lower 16-byte boundary, clobbering the adjacent chunk's header and
+   corrupting the heap.  Honor the compiler's biggest alignment when it
+   exceeds the historical default so plain malloc satisfies vector
+   types even under language modes without over-aligned operator new. */
+#if defined(__BIGGEST_ALIGNMENT__) && (__BIGGEST_ALIGNMENT__ > (SIZE_SZ + SIZE_SZ))
+#define MALLOC_ALIGNMENT       __BIGGEST_ALIGNMENT__
+#else
 #define MALLOC_ALIGNMENT       (SIZE_SZ < 4 ? 8 : (SIZE_SZ + SIZE_SZ))
+#endif
+#define MALLOC_ALIGN           MALLOC_ALIGNMENT
 #else
 #define MALLOC_ALIGN           MALLOC_ALIGNMENT
 #endif
